snippet.textDisplay:
The Mega Sg has little to nothing to do with Sega themselves (the fact it doesn't have Sega anywhere in the name should already be a hint). It's made by Analogue, who made the Super Nt (reviewed on LTT), and it's a hardware based device (not a software emulator) to make those old Sega games easily compatible with modern TVs, among other things like better audio quality. It doesn't come with any games by itself, and only supports cartridges (and Sega CD via an adapter), so it's got nothing to do with the popular "Mini" consoles being launched by Nintendo and others, that are based on a fairly generic board running an emulator with built-in games.

Sega IS planning to enter the field though with a Mega Drive Mini in 2019, which will be a very similar product to the NES and SNES Minis.
